entry.title: Reland^3 "android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 58b4a751dbb46c62d2874e507417f5a9a1f63452.



Reason for revert: Added pgo to failing bots (separate commits)





> > Original change's description:

> > > android: Make arm64 builds HighEnd by default

> > >

> > > The most popular arm64 builds (Trichrome) are shipping with

> > > is_high_end_android. The Monochrome arm64 builds are shipped for old

> > > devices, and we expect these to gradually become less popular.

> > >

> > > This change sets is_high_end_android to true for arm64 builds by

> > > default.

> > >

> > > This would make local benchmarking slightly less error prone because

> > > there would be a little less to remember to set in GN args when making a

> > > build for the most popular official configuration.

> > >

> > > Known effects:

> > >

> > > 1. Seemingly all official arm64 builders now explicitly set

> > > is_high_end_android. Hence no effect for them.

> > >

> > > 2. Non-official arm64 builders will change to become high-end, even the

> > > ones that end up running on old devices (example: android-arm64-rel).

> > > In this patch we make sure that is_high_end_android is ignored for

> > > non-official builds (disabled RELR relocations for non-official).

> > > Hence, no effect here as well.

> > >

> > > 3. Official builds of Monochrome made by devs would fail to run on

> > > Android pre-P (because RELR support is lacking). This leads to

> > > mysterious crashes during something-dlopen in the Android dynamic

> > > linker. Hopefully nobody does this before we remove support for

entry.title: [UPMLocalSettings] Introduce second password check
entry.content:
There will be 2 password checks in the safety check UI:

- The check for passwords stored in the local storage

- The check for passwords stored in the account storage (meaning that

those passwords sync across user devices)



Both checks will be displayed only if sync is on and the

upm-local-no-migration feature flag is enabled.



For each of the checks the corresponding password check model is

created in the coordinator, mPasswordCheckLocalModel and

mPasswordCheckAccountModel. Any of the models can be null (e. g. if

sync is off mPasswordCheckAccountModel is null; if sync is on but

entry.title: Remove mDeveloperModeEnabled flag from WebView
entry.content:
The purpose of this flag was to attempt to avoid restarting the service

and setting up a new notification if it was already present. However,

due to the complex state the service can get in, it could sometimes be

misleading.



By removing the flag, there is now a single source of truth for whether

or not developer mode is enabled: The component state in the package

manager. Apps using WebView can query this information to decide if they

should interact with the developer mode service.



When an app decides that it needs to interact with developer mode, and

attempts to start the service, this will now result in a full

re-initialisation of the service.



This will happen once for every app that starts up, but should not slow

down the app startup, since it will still be able to use the

ContentProvider to query the flags while the service is re-setting the

notification.



A failed service startup (e.g. if the requesting app is not in the

foreground) will no longer have the option of leaving the service in an

invalid state.

entry.title: [Autofill] Move focus tracking from client to popup controller
entry.content:
This CL replaces the focus-tracking using

WebContentsObserver::OnWebContentsLostFocus() and

WebContentsObserver::OnWebContentsFocused()

with checking RenderWidgetHostView::HasFocus().



At least in Aura, both are apparently equivalent:

The new code uses RenderWidgetHostView::HasFocus(), which is

defined in terms of FocusClient::GetFocusedWindow(), which is

implemented by FocusController and HeadlessFocusClient.

FocusController::GetFocusedWindow() is defined by

FocusController::SetFocusedWindow(), which is where through

FocusChangeObserver::OnWindowFocused() the callpaths of

WebContentsObserver::OnWebContentsFocused() and

WebContentsObserver::OnWebContentsLostFocus() start. Similarly for

HeadlessFocusClient.



I haven't checked for Android (because it goes through JNI) and

Mac (because Obj-C++).

entry.content:
[1] restricted the ExternalVkImageBackingFactory short-circuit out when

the SI is using external sampling to short-circuit out only when GL

interop is needed (as specified by the SharedImage usage). We can

SHARED_IMAGE_USAGE_GLES2_FRAMEBUFFER_HINT (which effectively means a

> [A11y / FaceGaze]: Don't respond to synthesized events

>

> Upon making the mouse updates faster in crrev.com/c/5207489,

> found that the mouse position callback to Javascript was

> occurring later than the previous mouse position was sent in.

> This is fixed by not sending synthetic mouse events to the

> extensions.

>

> This change also adds a timeout after the last non-synthetic mouse

> move or drag during which FaceGaze doesn't appear to update the

> cursor position; this allows a user to use a mouse or trackpad to
